    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "First, let me give you a quick recap on what you need to do: choose a soil mix that is well-draining but moisture-retentive, and then repot your fiddle leaf fig in a way that minimizes stress. You can do this by using a mix of peat moss, perlite, and a bit of orchid bark, or a pre-mixed potting soil designed for houseplants. Make sure the new pot is only 1-2 inches larger in diameter than the current one to avoid excessive root growth and keep the plant stable.\n\nWhen repotting, be gentle to avoid damaging the roots. Carefully remove the plant from its current pot, trim any overly long or tangled roots, and place it into the new pot with the soil mix. Water the plant lightly after repotting and keep it in a location with bright, indirect light for a few days to help it recover. This process should help your fiddle leaf fig thrive and stop the leaf drop.",
